column1: What does `DataLoaders` do in the fast.ai library?
column2:
The `DataLoaders` library provides a set of generic functions that make it easy to load data into memory and then vectorize it. `DataLoaders` can help make your code more concise and easier to read, especially when you are working with a lot of different datasets or tasks. In fast.ai courses, we have used `DataLoaders` for a wide range of applications, including:
  • Load log data from Amazon Athena, so that we can perform basic analytics on user behavior
  • Load images from Twitter, in order to perform object detection or segmentation
  • Load embedding matrices (e.g. Word2vec and Glove vectors) from disk
  • Load CSV files from Amazon S3, so that we can clean them, analyze the contents and compute statistics
  • Load sparse matrices or array-valued Python objects from disk, so that they can be used in matrix multiplications
  • Load large sparse matrices from disk, in order to do matrix-vector or matrix-matrix multiplications
  • Generate training data (e.g. sequences of words or images) in memory

What types of problems might `DataLoaders` be useful for?

The applications that we have described previously are just a small sample of the types of tasks that you might be able to accomplish with `DataLoaders`. For example, elsewhere in this course, we will use `DataLoaders` to load and tokenize sentence data from files, in order to perform language modeling and sequence labeling.

How does `DataLoaders` compare to other libraries?

To understand how `DataLoaders` compares to other libraries, it is important to know that there are many ways to load data. Two of the most popular options are the `zip` function, which is built into Python, and the `torch `_ library, which is one of the most commonly used frameworks for deep learning. In this section, we will highlight some of the main differences between `DataLoaders` and these two existing libraries
